f data transfer speeds of 13.1 Gbit/sec and above, or about 20 times the speed of current TransferJet. This specification uses the 60&nbsp;GHz band and requires only 2&nbsp;msec or less to establish a connection prior to the actual data transfer, thereby enabling the exchange of large content files even in the short amount of time it takes, for example, for a person to walk through a wicket gate. The TransferJet Consortium is currently defining the details of the TransferJet X ecosystem, based on the IEEE 802.15.3e standard<ref>http://www.techstreet.com/ieee/standards/ieee-802-15-3e-2017?product_id=1922221</ref> completed and published in June 2017. The HRCP Research and Development Partnership<ref>http://www.hrcp.jp/en/</ref>, established in 2016, is developing an [[System on a chip|SoC]] solution for implementing TransferJet X in a variety of products and services to be released starting around 2020. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.transferjet.org/  Transferjet.org: '''TransferJet Consortium''' official website]\n\n{{Prone to spam|date=November 2018}}\n{{Z148}}<!--     {{No more links}}\n\n       Please be cautious adding more external links.\n\nWikipedia is not a collection of links and should not be used for advertising.\n\n     Excessive or inappropriate links will be removed.\n\n See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.\n\nIf there are already suitable links, propose additions or replacements on\nthe article's talk page.\n\n-->\n\n\n{{Sony Corp|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Interfaces]]\n[[Category:Electrical connectors]]\n[[Category:Network protocols]]\n[[Category:Sony hardware]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2008]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TransferJet"}
{"title_page": "Tragedy (Bee Gees song)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Tragedy\n| cover      = Bee-Gees-Tragedy.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bee Gees]]\n| album      = [[Spirits Having Flown]]\n| B-side     = Until\n| released   = February 1979\n| format     = [[7\" single]], [[45rpm]]\n| recorded   = 1978\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Disco-rock]]\n| length     = 5:03\n| label      = [[RSO Records|RSO]]\n| writer     = [[Barry, Robin & Maurice Gibb]]\n| producer   = Bee Gees, [[Albhy Galuten]], Karl Richardson\n| prev_title = [[Too Much Heaven]]\n| prev_year  = 1978\n| next_title = [[Love You Inside Out]]\n| next_year  = 1979\n| misc       = {{External music video|type=single|{{YouTube|gSq_KmikENc|\"Tragedy (Live in Las Vegas, 1997 - One Night Only)\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Tragedy'''\" is a song released by the [[Bee Gees]], written by [[Barry, Robin & Maurice Gibb]], included on their 1979 album ''[[Spirits Having Flown]]''. The single reached number one in the [[UK Singles Chart|UK]] in February 1979 and repeated the feat the following month on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. In New Zealand, Tragedy succeeded the number 1 hit for 6 weeks from 18 March - 22 April.\n\n==Origin==\n[[Barry Gibb|Barry]], [[Robin Gibb|Robin]] and [[Maurice Gibb]] wrote this song and \"[[Too Much Heaven]]\" in an afternoon off from making the ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (film)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' movie, in which they were starring. In the same evening, they wrote \"[[Shadow Dancing (song)|Shadow Dancing]]\", which was performed by [[Andy Gibb]] (and reached number one in the US).<ref>[http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=5545 Tragedy Songfacts]</ref>\n\nThough not originally in ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]'', it has subsequently been added to the musical score of the [[West End theatre|West End]] version of the movie-[[Musical theatre|musical]]. The song knocked \"[[I Will Survive]]\" by [[Gloria Gaynor]] off the top spot in the US for two weeks before that song again returned to number one for an additional week. \"Tragedy\" was the second single out of the three released from the album to interrupt a song's stay at number one. In the US, it would become the fifth of six consecutive number-ones in a single year, tying the record with [[Bing Crosby]], [[Elvis Presley]], and [[the Beatles]] for most consecutive number-ones in the US in a single year.\n\nIn 1979, [[NBC]] aired ''[[The Bee Gees Special]]'', which showed how the sound effect for the explosion was created. Barry cupped his hands over a microphone and made an exploding sound with his mouth. Several of these sounds were then mixed together creating one large boom heard on the record.\n\n==In other media==\n\"Tragedy\" is playable as downloadable content for ''[[Rock Band 3]]'' and ''[[Rock Band 4]]''.\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n\n===Chart performance===\n====Weekly charts====\n{{col-begin|width=77%}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1979)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|2|artist=Bee Gees|song=Tragedy}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|3|artist=Bee Gees|song=Tragedy}}\n|-\n|[[Canadian dance chart|Canadian ''RPM'' Disco Singles]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0117&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |title=Tragedy in Canadian Disco Singles Chart |publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]] |accessdate=2 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110175025/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0117&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |archivedate=10 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-