{"title_page": "Tony Longhurst", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2010}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Tony Longhurst\n| image             =\n| imagesize         =\n| caption           =\n| nationality       = Australian\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1957|10|1}}\n| birth_place       = Sydney\n| death_date        =\n| death_place       =\n| retired           =\n| related to        =\n| last series       = [[Australian Touring Car Championship|ATCC]] / [[Supercars Championship|V8 Supercar]]\n| years active      = 1985\u20132007\n| teams             = [[JPS Team BMW]]<br>[[LoGaMo Racing|Tony Longhurst Racing]]<br>[[Longhurst Racing]]<br>[[Stone Brothers Racing]]<br>[[Rod Nash Racing]]<br>[[Holden Racing Team]]<br>[[Perkins Engineering]]<br>[[Team Dynamik]]\n| starts            = 191\n| wins              = 5\n| poles             =\n| fastest laps      = <!-- if known -->\n| best finish       = 3rd\n| year              = [[1991 Australian Touring Car Championship|1991]] & [[1992 Australian Touring Car Championship|1992]]\n| prev series       = Alfasud Series<br>AMSCAR<br>[[Australian Super Touring Championship|Australian Super Touring]]\n| prev series years = 1983<br>1986\u201391<br>1994\n| titles            = AMSCAR<br>AMSCAR<br>[[Bathurst 1000]]<br>AMSCAR<br>AMSCAR<br>AMSCAR<br>[[Australian Super Touring Championship|Australian Super Touring]]<br>[[Bathurst 1000]]<br>[[Bathurst 12 Hour]]\n| title years       = 1986<br>1987<br>[[1988 Bathurst 1000|1988]]<br>1989<br>1990<br>1991<br>1994<br>[[2001 Bathurst 1000|2001]]<br>[[2009 WPS Bathurst 12 Hour|2009]]\n| awards            =\n| award years       =\n}}\n\n'''Anthony Lawrence Longhurst''' (born 1 October 1957 in Sydney) is an Australian racing driver and former Australian Champion water skier. He is most noted for his career in the [[Australian Touring Car Championship]] and [[Supercars Championship|V8 Supercar]] series.\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Longhurst-sierra.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Ford Sierra RS500]] Longhurst drove to win [[1988 Bathurst 1000]]]]\nLonghurst is a two-time winner of the [[Bathurst 1000]], winning the event in 1988 with [[Tomas Mezera]]<ref>[https://news.google.com.au/newspapers?id=M2ERAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_JYDAAAAIBAJ&dq=tony%20longhurst&pg=5479%2C3183910 Sierras fill top three at Bathurst]</ref> and in 2001 with [[Mark Skaife]],<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_221142\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=221142&pnum=0 |title=Motorsport: Skaife supreme in topsy-turvy Bathurst race |date=8 October 2001 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=23 November 2011}}</ref> and is one of only four drivers to win Bathurst in both a [[Ford Motor Company of Australia|Ford]] and a [[Holden]] (the others being [[Craig Lowndes]], [[Steven Richards]] and [[Jamie Whincup]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/motorsport/richards-a-chip-off-the-old-block/2007/10/06/1191091420112.html?page=fullpage |title=Richards a chip off the old block |date=7 October 2007 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=23 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe has raced internationally in the [[1987 World Touring Car Championship season|1987 World Touring Car Championship]] and [[1993 FIA Touring Car Challenge]], both times for [[BMW]]. He also won the [[Australian Super Touring Championship]] for BMW in [[1994 Australian Manufacturers' Championship|1994]].\n\nAfter four years of service to the [[Frank Gardner (racing driver)|Frank Gardner]] run [[JPS Team BMW]] from 1984 to 1987, Longhurst started his own touring car team in 1988, which became known as [[LoGaMo Racing]], which based itself on the Gold Coast behind the Longhurst family owned [[Dreamworld (Australian theme park)|Dreamworld]]. For sponsorship reasons the team was known by various names during its time including [[Amatil|Freeport]] Motorsport and [[Benson & Hedges]] Racing. Initially running the powerful [[Ford Sierra RS500]] from 1988 to 1990, the team then began using the evolution model [[E30 M3|BMW M3]] (1991\u201393), before running a [[Holden Commodore VP]] supplied by [[Perkins Engineering]] in [[1994 Australian Touring Car season|1994]]. Longhurst saw particular success at [[Lakeside International Raceway]], winning three [[Lakeside ATCC round|rounds]] at the circuit in 1988, 1991 and 1992. In 1995, Longhurst sold out to fellow shareholders Gardner and Terry Morris and formed [[Longhurst Racing]] to compete in the [[Australian Touring Car Championship]] with a [[Ford Falcon EF]].\n\nTony Longhurst is the only driver to have won five of the now defunct AMSCAR series run at Sydney's [[Amaroo Park]] circuit. He won the series in 1986 ([[BMW E30|BMW 325i]]), 1987 (BMW M3), 1989 and 1990 (Ford Sierra RS500) and 1991 (BMW M3 Evolution).\n\nIn 1992 he also won the NZ Wellington street race in BMW M3. Came 3rd in 1989 Wellington street race and 3rd 1989 and 2nd in 1986 in the Pukekohe Nissan Mobil race in NZ.\n\nIn 2005, Longhurst bought the license for [[Team Dynamik]]'s second car, running the No. 45 car for [[Max Wilson]] under [[WOW Sight & Sound]] sponsorship. Following [[Simon Wills]]'s rollover at the Sandown 500, Longhurst purchased the remaining license from Team Dynamik and replaced Wills as Wilson's co-driver for the following round at Bathurst. He announced his retirement from competitive racing after the [[2005 Bathurst 1000]], where he and Brazilian co-driver [[Max Wilson]] failed to finish the race. He also made an appearance at the [[Targa Tasmania]] that year. He returned to this event in 2006, finishing fourth overall.\n\nLonghurst made two subsequent returns to the V8 Supercar Championship Series. In 2006, he was co-driver for Steve Owen in the [[Rod Nash Racing]] AutoBarn Commodore. The pair put in solid drives finishing 12th at Sandown and 7th at Bathurst. Longhurst's final drive came at the 2007 Sandown 500 where he paired with Glenn Seton following a series of last minute driver swaps in the Holden Racing Team following Mark Skaife having surgery to remove his appendix.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=Michael |title=Skaife ruled out of Sandown after appendix surgery |url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/motorsport/skaife-ruled-out-of-sandown-after-appendix-surgery-20070914-ge5tmd.html |work=The Age |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 he added a [[Bathurst 12 Hour]] victory, co-driving with Rod Salmon and Damien White.<ref>[http://www.motorsport.com/news/article.asp?ID=319478&FS= Bathurst 12: Event race report]</ref> By winning the 12 Hour, Longhurst joined [[Allan Grice]], [[Gregg Hansford]], [[Dick Johnson (racing driver)|Dick Johnson]] and [[John Bowe (racing driver)|John Bowe]] as winners of both the [[Bathurst 1000]] and Bathurst 12 Hour races (this list was later joined by [[Paul Morris (racing driver)|Paul Morris]] and [[Jonathon Webb]]).\n\nIn 2016, Longhurst returned to competition making an appearance at the [[Sydney Motorsport Park]] round of the [[2016 Australian GT Championship|Australian GT Championship]] in a Marque Sports [[Ford Focus]] and at the [[Silverstone Classic]] driving his [[1994 Australian Manufacturers' Championship]] winning [[BMW E36|BMW 318i]] [[Super Touring]] car.<ref>[http://www.speedcafe.com/2016/07/01/longhurst-eyes-bathurst-amid-race-return/ Longhurst eyes Bathurst amid race return] ''[[Speedcafe]]'' 1 July 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.speedcafe.com/2016/06/25/longhurst-to-race-to-win-title-winning-bmw/ Longhurst to race title winning BMW at Silverstone] ''Speedcafe'' 25 June 2016</ref>\n\nThe Benson & Hedges Ford Sierra RS500 driven by Longhurst and Tomas Mezera to victory at [[Bathurst 1000|Bathurst]] in 1988 (''pictured right'') is on display at the [[National Motor Racing Museum]] which is located on the outside of the final turn of the famous [[Mount Panorama Circuit]].\n\nLonghurst continues to live on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] in [[Queensland]] and owns and manages the Boat Works facility at [[Coomera]].<ref>[http://www.oceanmagazine.com.au/j/index.php/livenews/1276-the-boat-works-rising The Boat Works Rising] ''Ocean Magazine'' 14 August 2015</ref>\n\nLonghurst will return to Bathurst for the first time since winning the [[2009 WPS Bathurst 12 Hour]] when he will drive at the [[2017 Liqui Moly Bathurst 12 Hour]] driving a [[BMW M6 GT3]] for BMW Team SRM alongside [[Timo Glock]], [[Mark Skaife]] and [[Russell Ingall]].\n\n==Career results==\nSourced from Driver Database<ref>[https://www.driverdb.com/drivers/tony-longhurst/ Tony Longhurst at Driver Database]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Season\n! Series\n! Position\n! Car\n! Team\n|-\n! 1983\n| [[1983 Australian Endurance Championship|Australian Endurance Championship]]\n|align=\"center\" | 65th\n| [[Chevrolet Camaro (second generation)#1979|Chevrolet Camaro Z28]]\n| [[Mike Burgmann]]\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 1984\n| Alfasud Series\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| [[Alfa Romeo Alfasud]]\n| [[Longhurst Racing]]\n|-\n| [[1984 Australian Endurance Championship|Australian Endurance Championship]]\n|align=\"center\" | NC\n| [[BMW E24|BMW 635 CSi]]\n|rowspan=2| [[JPS Team BMW]]\n|-\n| [[1984 World Sportscar Championship season|World Sportscar Championship]]\n|align=\"center\" | NC\n| [[BMW E21|BMW 320i]]\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 1985\n| [[1985 Australian Touring Car Championship|Australian Touring Car Championship]]\n|align=\"center\" | 16th\n|rowspan=2| [[BMW E30|BMW 323i]]\n|rowspan=3| [[JPS Team BMW]]\n|-\n| [[Better Brakes AMSCAR Series|AMSCAR Series]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| '''2nd'''\n|-\n| [[1985 Australian Endurance Championship|Australian Endurance Championship]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| '''2nd'''\n| [[BMW E30|BMW 323i]]<br>[[BMW E24|BMW 635 CSi]]\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 1986\n| [[Better Brakes AMSCAR Series|AMSCAR Series]]\n|al