{"title_page": "Tommy Hunter (baseball)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name        = Tommy Hunter\n|image       = Tommy Hunter 2018 (cropped).jpg\n|width       = 280px\n|caption     = Hunter with the Philadelphia Phillies in 2018\n|team        = Philadelphia Phillies\n|number      = \n|position    = [[Relief pitcher]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1986|7|3}}\n|birth_place = [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]]\n|bats        = Right\n|throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate   = August 1\n|debutyear   = 2008\n|debutteam   = Texas Rangers\n|statyear    = 2019 season\n|statleague  = MLB\n|stat1label  = [[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value  = 56\u201344\n|stat2label  = [[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value  = 4.08\n|stat3label  = [[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value  = 566\n|teams       = \n* [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] ({{mlby|2008}}\u2013{{mlby|2011}})\n* [[Baltimore Orioles]] ({{mlby|2011}}\u2013{{mlby|2015}})\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2015}})\n* [[Cleveland Indians]] ({{mlby|2016}})\n* [[Baltimore Orioles]] ({{mlby|2016}})\n* [[Tampa Bay Rays]] ({{mlby|2017}})\n* [[Philadelphia Phillies]] ({{mlby|2018}}\u2013present)\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World University Baseball Championship|World University Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[World University Baseball Championship|2006 Havana]] | [[United States national baseball team|National team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Raymond Thomas Hunter''' (born July 3, 1986) is an American professional [[baseball]] [[relief pitcher]] for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played for the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], [[Chicago Cubs]], [[Cleveland Indians]], [[Baltimore Orioles]] and [[Tampa Bay Rays]].\n\nHunter was drafted by the Rangers in the supplemental first round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball Draft]] out of the [[University of Alabama]]. He made his major league debut in 2008. In 2010 he led the [[American League]] with a .765 win-loss percentage, as he was 13\u20134.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nHunter was born to Ray and Pam Hunter in [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]], and raised there with his older sister Megan.<ref name=autogenerated3>[https://rolltide.com/news/2006/2/1/33_Tommy_Hunter.aspx?path=baseball 33 Tommy Hunter - University of Alabama Athletics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Hunter attended [[Cathedral High School (Indianapolis)|Cathedral High School]], where he was a two-time All-City Player of the Year (2004 and 2005) .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/sports/baseball/2014/03/18/cathedral-alum-tommy-hunter-settling-into-baltimore-orioles-closer-role/6559061/|title=Cathedral alum Tommy Hunter settling into Orioles' closer role|date=March 18, 2014|work=Indianapolis Star|accessdate=April 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated3 /> He played both baseball and football for the school.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/player/488984/tommy-hunter|title=Tommy Hunter Stats, Fantasy & News|website=Philadelphia Phillies}}</ref> He was also a two-time Junior Olympic [[judo]] champion.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> \n\nHunter married girlfriend Ellen Cohara on January 4, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.camdenchat.com/2014/7/29/5946255/get-to-know-your-orioles-tommy-hunter|title=Get to know your Orioles: Tommy Hunter|work=Camden Chat|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref> They have two sons, Henry and Oliver.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==College==\nHunter attended the [[University of Alabama]] for two years.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> At Alabama, Hunter played for the [[Alabama Crimson Tide baseball|Alabama Crimson Tide]] and was a Second-Team [[All-American]] in his freshman season, during which the team won the 2006 [[Southeastern Conference]] Championship, and a pre-season All-American entering his sophomore season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2015/07/former_alabama_star_tommy_hunt.html|title=MLB Trade Deadline 2015: Former Alabama star Tommy Hunter changes wild-card races in trade|work=AL.com|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> He also earned a gold medal at the [[World University Baseball Championship]] with the USA National Baseball Team in 2006.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==Major league career==\n===Texas Rangers (2008\u201311)===\n[[File:Tommy Hunter.JPG|thumb|left|Hunter with the Texas Rangers]]\nHunter was drafted by the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in the supplemental first round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball Draft]] out of the University of Alabama, and signed for a $585,000 [[signing bonus]].<ref>[http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?ID=128940 Tommy Hunter - The Baseball Cube<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The Rangers were awarded a compensatory pick when [[Mark DeRosa]] left to go to the [[Chicago Cubs]] in [[Free agent|free agency]].\n\nHunter made his major league debut on August 1, 2008, taking on the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] as the fourth-youngest player in the American League shortly after turning 22 years of age.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=https://thebaltimorewire.com/2016/08/28/baltimore-orioles-bring-tommy-hunter-back-big-games|title=Baltimore Orioles Bring Tommy Hunter Back for Big Games|work=Baltimore Wire}}</ref> He pitched 11 innings for the Rangers in 2008.<ref name=autogenerated4>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/h/hunteto02.shtml Tommy Hunter Stats | Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He recorded his first MLB win on July 3, 2009, against the [[Tampa Bay Rays]]. He recorded his first Major League complete game on September 13 against the [[Seattle Mariners]]. On October 3 Hunter gave up [[Ken Griffey Jr]]'s 630th career [[home run]].\n\nIn 2009, he was 9-6 with a 4.10 ERA, with 64 strikeouts in 112 innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He held right-handed hitters to a .228 batting average (7th-lowest in the AL), and opponents at home to a .226 average (the lowest single-season figure ever by a pitcher with at least 10 starts at [[Rangers Ballpark]]).<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nHunter made his 2010 season debut on June 5, pitching a complete game win against the [[Tampa Bay Rays]]. He was 13\u20134 for the season (an American League-leading .765 win-loss percentage), with a 3.73 ERA as he struck out 68 batters in 128 innings.<ref name=autogenerated1 />  His 13 wins tied [[Derek Holland]] for the most wins by any pitcher in the Rangers organization in 2010, in either the major or minor leagues.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Hunter started Game 4 of the ALCS vs the [[New York Yankees|Yankees]].\n\nIn 2011 with the Rangers he was 1-1 with a 2.93 ERA, and struck out 10 batters in 15.1 innings.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\n===Baltimore Orioles (2011\u201315)===\n[[File:Tommy Hunter on August 10, 2011.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Hunter with the Baltimore Orioles]]\n\nOn July 30, 2011, the Rangers traded Hunter and [[first baseman]] [[Chris Davis (baseball)|Chris Davis]] to the [[Baltimore Orioles]] for reliever [[Koji Uehara]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/07/30/report-orioles-close-to-trading-koji-uehara-to-rangers-for-chris-davis/|title=Rangers to acquire Koji Uehara from Orioles for Chris Davis and Tommy Hunter|work=HardballTalk|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> In 2011 with Baltimore he was 3-3 with a 5.06 ERA, with 35 strikeouts in 69.1 innings.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nIn the 2012 season, Hunter posted a 7\u20138 record with a 5.45 ERA, with 77 strikeouts in 133.2 innings.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> He was a starter for a while, but was optioned to Triple A Norfolk. He was placed in the [[bullpen]] as a reliever. As a reliever Hunter's fastball averaged 96 [[Miles per hour|MPH]] over the month of September, and topped out at 100 MPH, after averaging 91-92 MPH for his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangraphs.com/blogs/index.php/tommy-hunter-or-generics-versus-the-brand-name/|title=Tommy Hunter, or Generics versus the Brand Name - FanGraphs Baseball|publisher=|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> In 2013, he was 6-5 with four saves and a 2.81 ERA and 68 strikeouts in 68.1 innings in 68 games, and held right-handed batters to a batting line of .141/.190/.154 in 159 plate appearances.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nAfter former closer [[Jim Johnson (baseball, born 1983)|Jim Johnson]] was traded to the [[Oakland Athletics]], Hunter was named the new Orioles closer for the 2014 season. Hunter started the 2014 season as the Orioles closer and was successful in 11 of his 12 [[save (baseball)|save]] opportunities, but he blew two consecutive saves on May 10 and 13 and then was placed on the 15-day [[disabled list]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tommy Hunter|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/11052064/baltimore-orioles-activate-tommy-hunter-15-day-disabled-list?ex_cid=espnapi_public|accessdate=September 17, 2014|publisher=ESPN.com}}</ref>  When he returned, he continued to work out of the bullpen, but not as the closer. For the 2014 season, he was 3-2 with 11 saves and a 2.97 ERA and 45 strikeouts in 60.2 innings in 60 games.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He agreed to a one-year deal worth $4.65 million in January 2015, avoiding arbitration.<ref>{{cite news|title=Orioles, Hunter agree on 1-year contract|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=12156949|accessdate=January 13, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN|date=January 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was 2-2 with Baltimore in 2015 with a 3.63 ERA with 32 strikeouts in 44.2 innings.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===Chicago Cubs (2015)===\nOn July 31, 2015, Hunter was traded to the [[Chicago Cubs]] for outfielder [[Junior Lake (baseball)|Junior Lake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/140132628|title=Cubs get Hunter from O's, send Lake in return|work=MLB.com|date=July 31, 2015|accessdate=July 31, 2015|first= Carrie|last= Muskat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Orioles/status/627214664175353856|title=Baltimore Orioles on Twitter|work=Twitter|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> He was 2-0 with one save with the Cubs with a 5.74 ERA with 15 strikeouts in 15.2 innings.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> After the season, he had two surgeries to repair a core muscle injury.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n===Cleveland Indians (2016)===\nHunter signed a one-year contract worth $2 million with the [[Cleveland Indians]] on February 12, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2016/02/cleveland_indians_sign_rhp_tom.html|title=Cleveland Indians sign RHP Tommy Hunter to 1-year deal worth $2 million|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> He was placed on the disabled list on July 17 after suffering a non-displaced fracture in his back following a fall at his home.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2016/07/cleveland_indians_recall_cody_1.html#incart_river_index|title=Cleveland Indians recall Cody Anderson; Tommy Hunter placed on disabled list|last=Hoynes|first=Paul|work=cleveland.com|date=July 17, 2016|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> On August 25, Hunter was released.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bastian|first1=Jordan|title=Veteran pitcher Hunter released by Tribe|url=http://m.indians.mlb.com/news/article/197644728/veteran-rhp-tommy-hunter-released-by-indians/|accessdate=August 29, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 25, 2016}}</ref> He was 2-2 with the Indians with a 3.74 ERA with 17 strikeouts in 21.2 innings.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===2nd stint Baltimore Orioles  (2016)===\nThe [[Baltimore Orioles]] signed Hunter on August 28, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Orioles sign RHP Tommy Hunter|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/17409282/baltimore-orioles-sign-rhp-tommy-hunter|accessdate=August 29, 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN|date=August 28, 2016}}</ref> He was 0-0 with the Orioles with a 2.19 ERA in 12 games.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n=== Tampa Bay Rays (2017) ===\n[[File:Tommy Hunter (baseball) 2017.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Hunter in 2017]]\nOn February 22, 2017, Hunter signed a minor league deal with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2017/02/rays-nearing-minor-league-deal-with-tommy-hunter.html|title=Rays, Tommy Hunter Agree To Minor League Deal|website=MLB Trade Rumors|language=en-US|access-date=2017-06-02}}</ref> Hunter impressed in [[spring training]] and received a spot in the bullpen. He had an ERA of 1.08 in 10 appearances before suffering a calf injury after running to first base on a ball in play. On April 23, Hunter was placed on the [[10-day disabled list|10-Day DL.]] He was activated off the DL on May 25th.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/players/playerpage/1595123/tommy-hunter|title=Tommy Hunter, RP, Tampa Bay Rays|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=2017-06-02|language=en}}</ref> \n\nHunter finished the season with a 3-5 record with one save and 25 [[Hold (baseball)|hold]]s (5th in the AL) in 61 games with a 2.61 ERA (a career low), pitching predominantly in the 8th inning before closer [[\u00c1lex Colom\u00e9|Alex Colom\u00e9]]. He held all hitters to a .202/.254/.333 batting line as he struck out 64 batters in 58.2 innings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/h/hunteto02.shtml|title=Tommy Hunter Stats {{!}} Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-13}}</ref>\n\n===Philadelphia Phillies (2018\u2013present)===\nOn December 15, 2017, Hunter signed a two-year contract with the [[Philadelphia Phillies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/phillies/news/phillies-sign-pitcher-tommy-hunter/c-263339958|title=Phillies add another bullpen piece in Hunter|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|work=MLB.com|date=December 15, 2017|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}</ref> He changed his number from 40 to 96 after [[Wilson Ramos]] was acquired from the [[Tampa Bay Rays|Rays]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2018/07/31/wilson-ramos-trade-phillies-rays/873483002/|title=NL East leading Phillies acquire All-Star catcher Wilson Ramos from Rays|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-08-03|language=en}}</ref> In 2018 with the Phillies, he was 5-4 with four saves, 25 holds (tied for 5th in the NL), and a 3.80 ERA, as he struck out 51 batters in 64 innings over 65 games.<ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=nl&qual=10&type=0&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=11,d National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Pitchers \u00bb Standard Statistics | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> \n\nHe began the 2019 season on the disabled list with a right forearm injury. He was placed on the disabled list on July 14 with a right forearm injury that cost him the first three months of the season.<ref>[https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2019/07/phillies-place-tommy-hunter-on-il-recall-edubray-ramos.html Phillies Place Tommy Hunter On IL, Recall Edubray Ramos - MLB Trade Rumors<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On July 23, he underwent season-ending surgery to repair the [[flexor]] tendon in his right arm.<ref>[https://mlb.nbcsports.com/2019/07/23/tommy-hunter-undergoes-surgery-to-repair-flexor-tendon/ Tommy Hunter undergoes surgery to repair flexor tendon \u2013 HardballTalk<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.inquirer.com/phillies/philadelphia-phillies-tommy-hunter-gabe-kapler-zach-eflin-jean-segura-injuries-mlb-20190723.html \"Phillies reliever Tommy Hunter is done for the season after undergoing surgery\"]</ref> In 2019, he was 0-0 with a 0.00 ERA in 5.1 innings over 5 games.<ref name=autogenerated4 />. On February 12,2020 Hunter resigned with the Phillies on a one year deal<ref>{{cite web|[https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2020/02/phillies-to-sign-tommy-hunter-html<!-- Bot generated title -->]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=488984|espn=29198|br=h/hunteto02|fangraphs=1157|brm=hunter001tom|retro=H/Phuntt002}}\n\n{{2007 MLB Draft}}\n{{Texas Rangers first-round draft picks}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Texas Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Tampa Bay Rays players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide baseball players]]\n[[Category:Spokane Indians players]]\n[[Category:Bakersfield Blaze players]]\n[[Category:Frisco RoughRiders players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma RedHawks players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma City RedHawks players]]\n[[Category:Round Rock Express players]]\n[[Category:Bowie Baysox players]]\n[[Category:Norfolk Tides players]]\n[[Category:Delmarva Shorebirds players]]\n[[Category:Columbus Clippers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name        = Tommy Hunter\n|image       = Tommy Hunter 2018 (cropped).jpg\n|width       = 280px\n|caption     = Hunter with the Philadelphia Phillies in 2018\n|team        = Philadelphia Phillies\n|number      = \n|position    = [[Relief pitcher]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1986|7|3}}\n|birth_place = [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]]\n|bats        = Right\n|throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate   = August 1\n|debutyear   = 2008\n|debutteam   = Texas Rangers\n|statyear    = 2019 season\n|statleague  = MLB\n|stat1label  = [[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value  = 56\u201344\n|stat2label  = [[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value  = 4.08\n|stat3label  = [[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value  = 566\n|teams       = \n* [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] ({{mlby|2008}}\u2013{{mlby|2011}})\n* [[Baltimore Orioles]] ({{mlby|2011}}\u2013{{mlby|2015}})\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2015}})\n* [[Cleveland Indians]] ({{mlby|2016}})\n* [[Baltimore Orioles]] ({{mlby|2016}})\n* [[Tampa Bay Rays]] ({{mlby|2017}})\n* [[Philadelphia Phillies]] ({{mlby|2018}}\u2013present)\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World University Baseball Championship|World University Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[World University Baseball Championship|2006 Havana]] | [[United States national baseball team|National team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Raymond Thomas Hunter''' (born July 3, 1986) is an American professional [[baseball]] [[relief pitcher]] for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played for the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], [[Chicago Cubs]], [[Cleveland Indians]], [[Baltimore Orioles]] and [[Tampa Bay Rays]].\n\nHunter was drafted by the Rangers in the supplemental first round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball Draft]] out of the [[University of Alabama]]. He made his major league debut in 2008. In 2010 he led the [[American League]] with a .765 win-loss percentage, as he was 13\u20134.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nHunter was born to Ray and Pam Hunter in [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]], and raised there with his older sister Megan.<ref name=autogenerated3>[https://rolltide.com/news/2006/2/1/33_Tommy_Hunter.aspx?path=baseball 33 Tommy Hunter - University of Alabama Athletics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Hunter attended [[Cathedral High School (Indianapolis)|Cathedral High School]], where he was a two-time All-City Player of the Year (2004 and 2005) .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/sports/baseball/2014/03/18/cathedral-alum-tommy-hunter-settling-into-baltimore-orioles-closer-role/6559061/|title=Cathedral alum Tommy Hunter settling into Orioles' closer role|date=March 18, 2014|work=Indianapolis Star|accessdate=April 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated3 /> He played both baseball and football for the school.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/player/488984/tommy-hunter|title=Tommy Hunter Stats, Fantasy & News|website=Philadelphia Phillies}}</ref> He was also a two-time Junior Olympic [[judo]] champion.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> \n\nHunter married girlfriend Ellen Cohara on January 4, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.camdenchat.com/2014/7/29/5946255/get-to-know-your-orioles-tommy-hunter|title=Get to know your Orioles: Tommy Hunter|work=Camden Chat|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref> They have two sons, Henry and Oliver.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==College==\nHunter attended the [[University of Alabama]] for two years.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> At Alabama, Hunter played for the [[Alabama Crimson Tide baseball|Alabama Crimson Tide]] and was a Second-Team [[All-American]] in his freshman season, during which the team won the 2006 [[Southeastern Conference]] Championship, and a pre-season All-American entering his sophomore season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2015/07/former_alabama_star_tommy_hunt.html|title=MLB Trade Deadline 2015: Former Alabama star Tommy Hunter changes wild-card races in trade|work=AL.com|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> He also earned a gold medal at the [[World University Baseball Championship]] with the USA National Baseball Team in 2006.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==Major league career==\n===Texas Rangers (2008\u201311)===\n[[File:Tommy Hunter.JPG|thumb|left|Hunter with the Texas Rangers]]\nHunter was drafted by the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in the supplemental first round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball Draft]] out of the University of Alabama, and signed for a $585,000 [[signing bonus]].<ref>[http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/profile.asp?ID=128940 Tommy Hunter - The Baseball Cube<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The Rangers were awarded a compensatory pick when [[Mark DeRosa]] left to go to the [[Chicago Cubs]] in [[Free agent|free agency]].\n\nHunter made his major league debut on August 1, 2008, taking on the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] as the fourth-youngest player in the American League shortly after turning 22 years of age.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=https://thebaltimorewire.com/2016/08/28/baltimore-orioles-bring-tommy-hunter-back-big-games|title=Baltimore Orioles Bring Tommy Hunter Back for Big Games|work=Baltimore Wire}}</ref> He pitched 11 innings for the Rangers in 2008.<ref name=autogenerated4>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/h/hunteto02.shtml Tommy Hunter Stats | Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He recorded his first MLB win on July 3, 2009, against the [[Tampa Bay Rays]]. He recorded his first Major League complete game on September 13 against the [[Seattle Mariners]]. On October 3 Hunter gave up [[Ken Griffey Jr]]'s 630th career [[home run]].\n\nIn 2009, he was 9-6 with a 4.10 ERA, with 64 strikeouts in 112 innings.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He held right-handed hitters to a .228 batting average (7th-lowest in the AL), and opponents at home to a .226 average (the lowest single-season figure ever by a pitcher with at least 10 starts at [[Rangers Ballpark]]).<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nHunter made his 2010 season debut on June 5, pitching a complete game win against the [[Tampa Bay Rays]]. He was 13\u20134 for the season (an American League-leading .765 win-loss percentage), with a 3.73 ERA as he struck out 68 batters in 128 innings.<ref name=autogenerated1 />  His 13 wins tied [[Derek Holland]] for the most wins by any pitcher in the Rangers organization in 2010, in either the major or minor leagues.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Hunter started Game 4 of the ALCS vs the [[New York Yankees|Yankees]].\n\nIn 2011 with the Rangers he was 1-1 with a 2.93 ERA, and struck out 10 batters in 15.1 innings.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\n===Baltimore Orioles (2011\u201315)===\n[[File:Tommy Hunter on August 10, 2011.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Hunter with the Baltimore Orioles]]\n\nOn July 30, 2011, the Rangers traded Hunter and [[first baseman]] [[Chris Davis (baseball)|Chris Davis]] to the [[Baltimore Orioles]] for reliever [[Koji Uehara]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/07/30/report-orioles-close-to-trading-koji-uehara-to-rangers-for-chris-davis/|title=Rangers to acquire Koji Uehara from Orioles for Chris Davis and Tommy Hunter|work=HardballTalk|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> In 2011 with Baltimore he was 3-3 with a 5.06 ERA, with 35 strikeouts in 69.1 innings.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nIn the 2012 season, Hunter posted a 7\u20138 record with a 5.45 ERA, with 77 strikeouts in 133.2 innings.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> He was a starter for a while, but was optioned to Triple A Norfolk. He was placed in the [[bullpen]] as a reliever. As a reliever Hunter's fastball averaged 96 [[Miles per hour|MPH]] over the month of September, and topped out at 100 MPH, after averaging 91-92 MPH for his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangraphs.com/blogs/index.php/tommy-hunter-or-generics-versus-the-brand-name/|title=Tommy Hunter, or Generics versus the Brand Name - FanGraphs Baseball|publisher=|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> In 2013, he was 6-5 with four saves and a 2.81 ERA and 68 strikeouts in 68.1 innings in 68 games, and held right-handed batters to a batting line of .141/.190/.154 in 159 plate appearances.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nAfter former closer [[Jim Johnson (baseball, born 1983)|Jim Johnson]] was traded to the [[Oakland Athletics]], Hunter was named the new Orioles closer for the 2014 season. Hunter started the 2014 season as the Orioles closer and was successful in 11 of his 12 [[save (baseball)|save]] opportunities, but he blew two consecutive saves on May 10 and 13 and then was placed on the 15-day [[disabled list]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tommy Hunter|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/11052064/baltimore-orioles-activate-tommy-hunter-15-day-disabled-list?ex_cid=espnapi_public|accessdate=September 17, 2014|publisher=ESPN.com}}</ref>  When he returned, he continued to work out of the bullpen, but not as the closer. For the 2014 season, he was 3-2 with 11 saves and a 2.97 ERA and 45 strikeouts in 60.2 innings in 60 games.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He agreed to a one-year deal worth $4.65 million in January 2015, avoiding arbitration.<ref>{{cite news|title=Orioles, Hunter agree on 1-year contract|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=12156949|accessdate=January 13, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN|date=January 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was 2-2 with Baltimore in 2015 with a 3.63 ERA with 32 strikeouts in 44.2 innings.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===Chicago Cubs (2015)===\nOn July 31, 2015, Hunter was traded to the [[Chicago Cubs]] for outfielder [[Junior Lake (baseball)|Junior Lake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/140132628|title=Cubs get Hunter from O's, send Lake in return|work=MLB.com|date=July 31, 2015|accessdate=July 31, 2015|first= Carrie|last= Muskat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Orioles/status/627214664175353856|title=Baltimore Orioles on Twitter|work=Twitter|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> He was 2-0 with one save with the Cubs with a 5.74 ERA with 15 strikeouts in 15.2 innings.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> After the season, he had two surgeries to repair a core muscle injury.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n===Cleveland Indians (2016)===\nHunter signed a one-year contract worth $2 million with the [[Cleveland Indians]] on February 12, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2016/02/cleveland_indians_sign_rhp_tom.html|title=Cleveland Indians sign RHP Tommy Hunter to 1-year deal worth $2 million|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> He was placed on the disabled list on July 17 after suffering a non-displaced fracture in his back following a fall at his home.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2016/07/cleveland_indians_recall_cody_1.html#incart_river_index|title=Cleveland Indians recall Cody Anderson; Tommy Hunter placed on disabled list|last=Hoynes|first=Paul|work=cleveland.com|date=July 17, 2016|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> On August 25, Hunter was released.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bastian|first1=Jordan|title=Veteran pitcher Hunter released by Tribe|url=http://m.indians.mlb.com/news/article/197644728/veteran-rhp-tommy-hunter-released-by-indians/|accessdate=August 29, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 25, 2016}}</ref> He was 2-2 with the Indians with a 3.74 ERA with 17 strikeouts in 21.2 innings.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===2nd stint Baltimore Orioles  (2016)===\nThe [[Baltimore Orioles]] signed Hunter on August 28, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Orioles sign RHP Tommy Hunter|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/17409282/baltimore-orioles-sign-rhp-tommy-hunter|accessdate=August 29, 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN|date=August 28, 2016}}</ref> He was 0-0 with the Orioles with a 2.19 ERA in 12 games.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n=== Tampa Bay Rays (2017) ===\n[[File:Tommy Hunter (baseball) 2017.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Hunter in 2017]]\nOn February 22, 2017, Hunter signed a minor league deal with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2017/02/rays-nearing-minor-league-deal-with-tommy-hunter.html|title=Rays, Tommy Hunter Agree To Minor League Deal|website=MLB Trade Rumors|language=en-US|access-date=2017-06-02}}</ref>. Hunter impressed in [[spring training]] and received a spot in the bullpen. He had an ERA of 1.08 in 10 appearances before suffering a calf injury after running to first base on a ball in play. On April 23, Hunter was placed on the [[10-day disabled list|10-Day DL.]] He was activated off the DL on May 25th.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/players/playerpage/1595123/tommy-hunter|title=Tommy Hunter, RP, Tampa Bay Rays|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=2017-06-02|language=en}}</ref> \n\nHunter finished the season with a 3-5 record with one save and 25 [[Hold (baseball)|hold]]s (5th in the AL) in 61 games with a 2.61 ERA (a career low), pitching predominantly in the 8th inning before closer [[\u00c1lex Colom\u00e9|Alex Colom\u00e9]]. He held all hitters to a .202/.254/.333 batting line as he struck out 64 batters in 58.2 innings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/h/hunteto02.shtml|title=Tommy Hunter Stats {{!}} Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-13}}</ref>\n\n===Philadelphia Phillies (2018\u2013present)===\nOn December 15, 2017, Hunter signed a two-year contract with the [[Philadelphia Phillies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/phillies/news/phillies-sign-pitcher-tommy-hunter/c-263339958|title=Phillies add another bullpen piece in Hunter|last=Zolecki|first=Todd|work=MLB.com|date=December 15, 2017|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}</ref> He changed his number from 40 to 96 after [[Wilson Ramos]] was acquired from the [[Tampa Bay Rays|Rays]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2018/07/31/wilson-ramos-trade-phillies-rays/873483002/|title=NL East leading Phillies acquire All-Star catcher Wilson Ramos from Rays|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-08-03|language=en}}</ref> In 2018 with the Phillies, he was 5-4 with four saves, 25 holds (tied for 5th in the NL), and a 3.80 ERA, as he struck out 51 batters in 64 innings over 65 games.<ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=nl&qual=10&type=0&season=2018&month=0&season1=2018&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=11,d National League Leaderboards \u00bb 2018 \u00bb Pitchers \u00bb Standard Statistics | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> \n\nHe began the 2019 season on the disabled list with a right forearm injury. He was placed on the disabled list on July 14 with a right forearm injury that cost him the first three months of the season.<ref>[https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2019/07/phillies-place-tommy-hunter-on-il-recall-edubray-ramos.html Phillies Place Tommy Hunter On IL, Recall Edubray Ramos - MLB Trade Rumors<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On July 23, he underwent season-ending surgery to repair the [[flexor]] tendon in his right arm.<ref>[https://mlb.nbcsports.com/2019/07/23/tommy-hunter-undergoes-surgery-to-repair-flexor-tendon/ Tommy Hunter undergoes surgery to repair flexor tendon \u2013 HardballTalk<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.inquirer.com/phillies/philadelphia-phillies-tommy-hunter-gabe-kapler-zach-eflin-jean-segura-injuries-mlb-20190723.html \"Phillies reliever Tommy Hunter is done for the season after undergoing surgery\"]</ref> In 2019, he was 0-0 with a 0.00 ERA in 5.1 innings over 5 games.<ref name=autogenerated4 />. On February 12,2020 Hunter resigned with the Phillies on a one year deal<ref>{{cite web|[https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2020/02/phillies-to-sign-tommy-hunter-html<!-- Bot generated title -->]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=488984|espn=29198|br=h/hunteto02|fangraphs=1157|brm=hunter001tom|retro=H/Phuntt002}}\n\n{{2007 MLB Draft}}\n{{Texas Rangers first-round draft picks}}\n{{Philadelphia Phillies roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Texas Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Tampa Bay Rays players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide baseball players]]\n[[Category:Spokane Indians players]]\n[[Category:Bakersfield Blaze players]]\n[[Category:Frisco RoughRiders players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma RedHawks players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma City RedHawks players]]\n[[Category:Round Rock Express players]]\n[[Category:Bowie Baysox players]]\n[[Category:Norfolk Tides players]]\n[[Category:Delmarva Shorebirds players]]\n[[Category:Columbus Clippers players]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Hunter_(baseball)"}
